{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_dean_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340582986/1920072301/0477.xml":{"full_text":"PROHIBITION HAS\nBEEN BENEFICIAL\n1 OPINION OF GARY\nHead of U. S. Steel Corpora\ntion Gives His Views on\nBusiness Outlook\nGenerally\nBy Associated Press\nNew York-, July 22.\u2014Prohibition has\nbeen beneficial to the nation's indus\ntrial and economic life, in the opinion\nof Elbert H. Gary, head of the United\nStates Steel Corporation, who issued a\n\u2022tatement here tonight on the eve of\nhis departure for Europe, giving hie\n\u25bclews on the business outlook gener\nally.\nThe prohibition laws have had\nimarked effect,\u201d he said. \u201cIn nearly\nievery newspaper one will read of fewer\nInmates of prisons, almshouses and hos\npitals, and larger balances in savings\nInstitutions and better, cleaner and\nhealthier conditions in the dwellings,\na.11 on account of prohibition.\n\u201cTestiAony on this subject is ac\ncumulated day by day. From an eco\nnomic pecuniary standpoint, 1 think a\nlarge majority of the people of this\ncountry are in favor of prohibition, and\nit is pleasing to note that the large\nnumbers of workmen, so far as 1 am\ninformed, subscribe to this view.\u201d\nBusiness conditions should be con\nsidered satisfactory, Mr. Gary said, al\nthough there has been \u201ca iack of pru\ndence in business management since\nfche armistice\u201d as regards prices.\nThe disposition to work and produce\nhas been materially diminished, accord\ning to Mr. Gary. He cited an instance\n\u2022by which he said in order to remove\nand replace a headlight on a locomo\nltiv\u00ab, \u201dit has been necessary to employ\n(four, different men because of labor\nregulations, where one man heretofore\nperformed the same service in less\ntime.\u201d\nTUBERCULOSIS CAUSED\nf>Q PER CENT DEATHS\nTwenty-one persons died of tubercu\nlosis during the month of June, ao\nItording to the monthly report of the\ncity heaJth department. A total of\nforty-two deaths from all communica\nble diseases was reported.\nThere were thirty-six more births\nthan deaths during June, according to\nthe report. Deaths: White, 111; blacks,\n12*. Total, 234. Births: White, 177;\nblack, 93. Total, 270. The birth rate\nwas about 3 per cent greater than for\nJune. 1919.\nThe clinic report shows that 2,34 9\ntreatments were given during the\nmonth. A total of 488 tests was given\nat the laboratory in connection with\nthis work.\nThe bureau of sanitation made 1#,\n727 inspections during the month. There\n\u25a0were eleven arrests and five convic\ntions daring the month for violation of\nsanitary ordinances.\nWAndercr Pleads Not Guilty\nBy Associated Press\nChicago, July 22.\u2014Carl Wanderer,\nself-confessed slayer of his wife and\na \u201cragged\u201d stranger who was used as\na dupe to stage a fake hold-up, today\nentered a plea of not guilty when his i\ncase was called, and Judge Pam set the i\ntrial for September 13.\nChildren Cry\nFOR FLETCHER\u2019S\nCASTORIA t\nBRIDGE CONTRACTORS\nNOTICE\n\u201cSealed bids\u201d will be received by\nthe undersigned at the office of\nMADISON COUNTY BOARD OF\nREVENUEtin Huntsville, Alabama,\nuntil July 31st, 1920, at 12 o\u2019clock,\nnoon, for the construction of a riveted\nsteel truss United States Standard\n120-foot span bridge with 16-foot\nroadway together with re-inforced\nconcrete sub-structnre. Full details\nand specifications on file at this of\nfice.\nThis bridge is to be erected 3 miles a\neast of Hobbs Island, a station on N.\nC. St. L. Ry. Bids will be con- p\nsidered for a complete job on both p\nbridge and sub-structure, or single\nbids on bridge and sub-structore sep-\narately. b\nConcrete sub-structure will contain v\napproximately 105 cubic yards Class 8\n\u201cA\u201d concrete and 10 cubic yards Class p\n\u201cB\u201d concrete, together with about 0\n100 yards of earth excavations.\nCertified eheck for $500.00 to ac- r\ncompany any and all bids. The right\nto reject any and all bids is hereby\nreserved.\nPresident Madison County Board of\nRevenue.\nC H. PULLEY,\nb\nBUEHLER BROS.\nBig Cash Market\nis now open and doing business six full days a week\nat 519 19th street, Ensley. We handle nothing but\nthe best of meats and sell at retail at wholesale\nprices. Our motto is: \u2018Sanitation, Honest Weights\nand Courteous Treatment. Call and see our\nSaturday Specials\nBeef Roasts.15c-25c\nPork Chops .40c\nSugar Cured Reg.\nHams.40c\nCream Cheese.35c\nPicnic Haras.27c\nPure Lard.25c\nNo. 5 Snowhite $1.05\nPork Shoulders, 2 to\n8 lbs.25c\nYours to Please,\nBUEHLER BROTHERS\n519 19th SL, Ensley\nPhone 169 Ensley\n4\nENSLEY\nStudio Cora Chapman Boterweg, Representative.\nThe Age-Herald maintains a special \u00a3ns\nley bureau for handling correspondence,\nadvertising and subscriptions. It is lo\noted at 1913 Avenue E, RusseU Bros.\nPhone Ensley 300.\nThe merchants and business men of\nthe Ensley district have entered a com\nplaint against, the unsatisfactory serv\nice rendered here by the local telephone\nexchange. J. H. Perkins, prominent reai\nestate man, said: \"The business covered\nby the Ensley exchange is extensive and\nincludes many important businesses which\nare wholly dependent on the telephone i\nservice for their own good and for the\ngood of the public which they serve.\nPoor service in this way hurts both the\nindividual and the public and decreases\nthe capacity of both.\nThe shortage of telephones and the In\nability to get new ones have hampered\nthe' district for some time, and during\ntho war the public, a.s well as individuals,\nwere considerate of the handicap, but the\nservice has been such of late that the\nbusiness men of the district have exhaust\ned their patience. If there is any help\nfor the situation l should he glad if the\nmanagement could find it.\"\nD. P. Knapp, president of the Emrtey\nMotor Company, said in regard to the\nsituation: \"The telephone situation in\nEnsley has become intolerable. While\nseme have secured better service through\npersonal efforts with the management, so\nfar I have had very little results. The\nmanagement has blamed the railroads and\nshortage of labor for their shortcomings\nso long that it has become a habit. If all\nbusinesses had suffered as much as the\nSouthern Bell Telephone Company would\nhave you believe, more than half the\ndistrict would he out of commission.\nSince the war everything has been on the\nincrease and the continuous cry of the\ntelephone company that labor and ma\nterial cannot he secured speakS bad for\nthe local organization of management.\"\nE. W. Kelly said: \"I have ceased strug\ngling. The service couldn\u2019t be worse.\"\nAn event of today will be a reception\nfof* Mrs. A. K. Wright of Louisville\nwith Mrs. Peyton A. Eubank hostess at\nher home, 2300 Avenue I. The hours will\nbe from 4 to 6 o\u2019clock.\nMrs. O. A_ Ganes, who has been visit\ning her mother here, has gone to Mon\ntreal, Canada to spend the remainder of\nthe summer.\nRev. and Mrs. A. K. Wright, who for\na number of years made their home in\nEr.sley, where Rev. Wright was pastor\nof the Ensley Baptist church, arrived\nyesterday to be the guests of Mr. and\nMrs. Peyton A. Eubank and other\nfriends. Among the affairs planned for\nthem will be a reception at the Baptist\nchurch next Tuesday evening, beginning\nat 8 o\u2019clock. The members of the con\ngregation and their friends are invited\nto attend.\nTHOM PSON -HO BBS\nThe following announcement will be of\ninterest to a number of people in the dis\ntrict where the groom is well known:\n\"Mrs. Maude lizabeth Hobbs announces\nthe marriage of her daughter. Lvnna\nYoung to Mr. Osbone Berney Thompson\non Tuesday. July 20, 1920, Jacksonville, 1\nAla. At home after August 1 at 2400 Ave\nnue I, Ensley, Ala.'1\nMiss Margaret Davis and Miss Ruth\nDavis were hostesses yesterday enter\ntaining at luncheon for Mrs. M. O.\nBlount, of Atlanta, Ga\u201e who is visiting\nfriends and relatives in the city.\nBright summer flowers made an at\ntractive centerpiece for the table and\ni overs were laid for ten.\nAn ice cream social will be given on\nthe lawn of Mrs. W. F. Shehee\u2019s home\nin Ensley avenue Saturday afternoon\nAnd evening from 4 to 9 o'clock. The\npublic is invited.\nG. A. Averyh has returned from a visit\n:o Tallahassee and Panacea, P'la.\nBY ESTELLE BETHEA HALE\nPOLLY, OZ AND CHICK\nFEATURE AT LXlliC\nFive unusually enjoyable acts are billed\nat the Lyric tor the later part of the\nweek. All the acts are well worth seeing,\nbut that Polly, U*z and Chick walk oh\nwith the highest honors will be unani\nmously agreed. They appear as a trio\nof exceeding cleverness and present sev\neral clever features. Among them the\nmost pleasing and original is a synco\npated marriage ceremony. If you have\nnever had the pleasure of witnessing a\nsyncopated marriage, you are having\nyour opportunity this week at the Lyric.\nJoe Darcy is good in a presentation of\nseveral songs written by himself. Dr\ncourse, no one is better able to render\na song more sympathetically than the\nwriter himself and Darcy gives some en\njoyable selections. Darcy is called a\nblack cloud with a silver lining. In other\nwords, he is a blackfaced comedian.\nLalla Selbini and Bert Nagle gave an\nact in which they did some good stunt\nwork.\nMarguerita Padula sang several songs\ndevoted to a study of boys. Marguerita\ntells the girls how to win them at first,\nor keep them at last and her advice is\ngood. Incidentally, the masculine part of\nher audience find it hard to keep their\nheads as Marguerita practices some of\nher wiles herself.\nChalk Face Foolery deals In opposites,\nfor it is really very amusing and clever\nsilent pantomine. It is, a daring thing\nto attempt to entertain several hundred\npeople without a word. This act is a\nreal success. How a bird wins his mate\n(with a diamond ring), is highly Instruc\ntive to young men, if hard to imitate.\nA Rex Beech story. \u201cGoing Some,\" is a\nfirst-class screen attraction.\nFAMOUS TENOR IS\nATTRACTION AT LOEWS\nFred Hughes, world-tamed Welsh\ntenor, is the headline attraction among\nthe five acts of vaudeville at Loew\u2019s\nBijou for the last half of the week.\nFred Hughes is well known in Bir\nmingham, and hundreds of music lovers\nhave his songs on their phonograph\nrecords. The songs that he is singing\nat the Bijou are making the same hit\ntoday as they did when he first( ap\npeared in Birmingham over two years\nago.\nThe La Temple performers, offering\nfeats of illusion and magic, are ac\ncounted among the very best illusion\nists in vaudeville. Their tricks are\nnew and startling. They received four\nencores.\nFealson and Wallace, who proved to\nbe very good comedians and also sing\ners of exceptional ability, offer a\nswitchboard comedy playlet which\nmakes an instant hit\nLynn, Weston and Lynn are seen to\nadvantage in a singing and dancing act\nThe young lady member of the trio\nputs the act across and her excellent\npiano playing won her several encores.\nSinclair and C.rey, two young misses\nin a cycling act, closed the vaudeville\nbill.\n\u201cThe Joyons Troublemakers,\u201d with\nWilliam Farnum in the title role, is the\nscreen attraction for the week-end. The\npicture is of the light comedy type and\ncontains many laugh-provoking and\nunusual situations. Several amusing\ncomedies and the International News\nreel of current events closed the bill.\n\u201cBURNING DAYLIGHT\u201d,\nAT THE ALCAZAR\nMight is not right, most certainly not\nThat was proven ages ago in the time of\ntournaments and knighthood. But where\nright has been ignored and forgotten,\nand where contracts are treated as mere\nscraps of paper,\u201d might Is one of right's\nbest known substitutes.\nAt any rate, Burning Daylight the\nhero of Jack London\u2019s story of the same\nname, being dramatized in a thrilling\npresentation at the Alcazar, finds him\nself in that position where a man must\nresort to prowess to secure fair treat\nment from a group of Wail street\n'\u25a0bears.\" Now, don't think for a mo\nment that this adventurous story is\nstaged on Wail street. liven with its\n\"bears,\" Wall street is no place for any\nself-respecting adventurer. \"Burning\nDaylight, owner of an Alaskan mine,\nonly visits \"Noo Yawk\u201d long enough to\nforce several intrigueing financiers to\nhand over what was distinctly his. Still\nmore distinctly not theirs. Readers of\nJack London stories, and lovers of thrill\ning outdoor life, will be in their element\nIn this pulsating story of the north.\nSUNDAY CONCERTS\nAT EDGEWOOD PARK\nSpecial entertainment. Including\nmusic by the Hillco jazz orchestra and\nsolos by Ben Tillson, baritone, has\nbeen arranged for Sunday at Mountain\nView Inn by the Kdgewood park man\nagement, according to announcement\nby Hugh Hill, president of the park\ncompany.\nArrangements have been made to\nhandle dinner guests in increased num\nbers from 12 until in the evening with\nout table reservations being made in\nadvance.\nIilxtra employes will handle the beach\ncrowds, and those who plan to make\nmerry in the water at Neptune have\nbeen promised the quickest possible\nservice.\nBeginning Sunday, all park busses\nwill meet South Highland cars at the\nend of the line to transport park pas\nsengers to the mountain resort, thus\nassuring quick transportation.\n\u201cINFERIOR SEX\u201d\nAT THE TRIANON\nWomen throw themselves too Intensely\ninto the marriage game to be winners.\nThey are too prone to drape themselves\nabout the husband's neck and there\ncling, regardless. To desire anything too\nongrossingly is the way to never possess\nit. This and the general idea of .^op\ning one's husband guessing is the theme\nof \"The Inferior Sex,\" at the Trianon\ntoday and Saturday. Mildred Chaplin\nHarris is the wife and a clinging vine\nuqrivaled. Later she is a turned worm\nwhen she finds that her adoration is\nmore of a bore to her beloved than\notherwise. As she turned worm she is\nas unrivaled as in the role of the per\nsistently adoring wife, and is fully as\npersistent.\nThe Inferior Sex'\u2019 is a heavy subject\nlightly treated. A most healthful mix\nture of humor and pathos, comedy and\nromance. It should please moviegoers of\nail tastes. Milton Sills, the leading man,\nis one of the most distinguished looking\nactors on the screen.\n\u201cSQUARE DEAL MAN*\nAT THE COLONIAL\nImagine a little slip of a woman order\ning big Bill Hart back to his work, and\nin general treating him as a servant and\na much inferior being! Well, it really is\ndone in \u201cThe Square Deal Man.\" a Hart\npiqture being shown at the Colonial for\nthe latter half of the week.\nOf course, it isn\u2019t done for long, and\nthe young lady, who is from the east,\nsoon learns that her eastern ideas of\nservants don\u2019t hold good among red\nblooded cowboys of the west. A few\ndesperate adventures and narrow es\ncapes soon teach her the value of a\nreal man in the great outdoors of the\nwest.\nSomehow even those who are not over\nfond of the adventurous type find a\nthrill in Hart\u2019s acting For Hart has a\nway of giving such well-balanced por\ntrayals. He possesses the unusual art\namong actors of the outdoor type of be\ning a good actor in softer scenes and\n\u25a0noro emotional or sentimental moments,\nrn other words, he is ifnlike many of\nthe red-blooded type, who jseem to find\nt so easy to face a lion, or several, for\n:hat matter, to make a thrilling rescue\n?f the heroine. But when it comes to\nhe love scene, usually following a res\n\u2022ue, they have to have a \u201cfade-out.\u201d\nS\u2019o wonder Hart is so popular with all\nunds of audiences.\n\\T THE RIALTO\n\u201cThe Country God Forgot,** a superb\n\u25a0>roduction of the north country, featur\nng Thomas Santschi and Mary Charle\nson, will be the attraction at the Rialto\nheater next week, beginning Monday.\nFhe story is laid in a country where\nforce rules, and w\u2019here no one has any\n\u2022egard for law. The best man wins.\nHelen Brant was happy with her hus\nband in the north country, the only coun\nry she had ever known, until the chap\n!rom the city stole her love. And then\ns unfolded one of the most gripping\niramas of the screen.\nFour Deputy Collectors\nAre Indicted for Murder\nand Held Without Bail\n\u25a0y Associated Proaa\nDanville. Va., July 22.\u2014Federal, Dep\nity Collectors of Internal Revenue J.\n'J. Wood and R. H. Drummond, and J.\n\u00bbV. Pugh and R. C. Wilmoth of the\n\u2019\u2019ittsylvania county constabulary, who\nissisted federal officers on July 14\nvhen Hosea Tomas, alleged liquor\nransporter. was shot to death near\n.eatherwood. Henry county, were today\nndicted for murder by a special*grand\nury in the Henry county circuit court.\nFederal Prohibition Attorney H.' C.\n*eck. who w'as present to represent the\ngovernment agents, made application\n\u2019or bail, but Judge Dillard promptly\njverruled the motion, holding that he\nlid not bail men charged with murdpr.\nr\nCALLS SELF \u201cRICHEST WOMAN\u201d\nNellie Kevell, theatrical press ayeiu, whose friends have rallied to Iter\nsupport as she lies to a plaster cast in a New York hospital. She calU\nherself the richest woman, not because she is ratling tn money, but be\ncause of the many friends she has.\nPEACE FIRST AND\nTHEN A LEAGUE IS\nHARDING\u2019S PROMISE\n{Continued from Page One)\nfriends from nearby counties mixed j\nwith the representatives of powerful\nrepublican clubs of distanct cities in j\nthe procession, gray with decorations\nand blatant with noise.\nAt the Chautauqua pavilion, where\nthe notification took place, seats had\nbeen provided for 4,000. and many times\nthat number surged about the park and\nsurrounding fields, unable to get within\nearshot of the speakers. The pro\nnouncements of the candidate were re\nceived with a tumult of applause and he\nwas cheered back to his home through\ncrowded streets, a tired but smiling\nman.\nWill H. Hays, the national chairman,\npresided at the ceremonies, and Sena\ntor Lodge of Massachusetts, who was\nchairman of th6 Chicago convention,\nformally notified the candidate of his\nnomination in a speech, rapping Presi\ndent Wilson\u2019s League of Nations and\npraising the part Sentaor Harding had\ntaken in preventing its unreserved ac\nceptance.\nSpeaking slowly and with a charac\nteristic gravity, the nominee delivered\nhis declaration of policy with a clear,\nfull voice that penetrated far into the\ncrowded outskirts of the pavilion.\nPoints he wished to drive home with\nparticular force he emphasized by ag\ngressive gestures, and several times he\ngot the crowd on its feet, cheering as\nhe hammered with clinched fist to em\nphasize his points.\nCHEER LEAGUE THRUSTS\nHis thrusts at the League of Nations\nwere answered by repeated thunderclaps\nof cheering, but the passage the crowd\nseemed to like best came almost at the\nend of the hour and a half of speaking,\nwhen he voiced his humility in the pres\nence of the responsibilities of the presi\ndency and then, squaring his broad\nshoulders, added that his confidence in\nthe support of his fellow citizens made\nhim \u2018\u2018wholly unafraid.\u201d\nIn his discussion of the league he made\nno direct recommendation for rejection\nof the peace treaty and did not take up\nin detail the league covenant. Content\ning himself with the declaration that the\nleague as conceived by the President was\nunthinkable, he passed on to state his\nown#view of what should be done.\n\u201cIn the call of the conscience of Ameri\nca is peace,\u201d he said, \u201cpeace that closes\nthe gaping wound 6f world war and si\nlences the impassioned voices of /inter\nnational envy and distrust. Heeding as\n1 do this call and knowing as T do the\ndisposition of Congress, I promise you\nformal and effective peace so quickly as\na republican Congres can pass its dec\nlaration for a republican executive to\nsign.\nWAY IS SIMPLE\n\"disposed as we are. the way is simple.\nLet the failure attending assumption, ob\nstinacy, impracticability and delay be rec\nognized and let us find the big, practical,\nunselfish way to do our part. With a\nSenate advising as the constitution con\ntemplates I would approach the nations\nof Europe and of the earth proposing that\nunderstanding which makes* us a will\ning participant in the consecration of na\ntions to a newT relationship, to commit\nthe moral forces of the world, America*\nincluded, to peace and international jus\ntice, still leaving America free, indepen\ndent and self-reliant, but offering friend\nship to all the world.\u201d\nAt the conclusion of the speech the\nsenator returned to his home, but sev\neral of the visiting delegations, not con\ntent with their first reception, called,\nagain to say good-by. With Mrs. Hard\ning, who had been by the side of the nom\ninee during most of the morning, he again\nshook hands with the callers. It was\nhis first big day of handshaking since\nhis nomination and he was tired out by\nthe time it wfas over.\nUNSATISFACTORY TO DRYS\nSenator Harding s attitude on prohi\nbition. as expressed in his speech of\nacceptance at Marion today, is \u201centire\nly unsatisfactory to the prohibition\nparty,\u201d Virgil G. Hinshavv, chairman\nof the national committee, said today.\n\u201cSenator Harding will receive no\nsupport from the prohibitionists, be\ncause he did not promise to use his\nveto power on ail bills repealing the\nm\nenforcement act,\u201d said Mr. Hinshaw.\n\"On the contrary he seems tQ invite\nIf\nYOUR CAPITAL\nCAN BE DOUBLED\nin ten years by investing it in a safe security paying 7 per cent in semi-annual\ndividends. Our preferred shares pay SV2 per cent in January and SV2 per cent\nin July of each year, and can be readily disposed of at par in the event of need\nto market them. The stock can be bought in sums of one hundred to five thou\nsand dollars.\nWe make loans on improved property in\nBirmingham, and discount well\nsecured mortgage notes and other\npurchase money paper\nRealty Trust Company\nJohn H. Frye, President John G. Farley, Vice President\nCapital Stock $600,000.00 303 North 20th Street\nThere\u2019s no end to the\nstocks of Estes Lumber\nor to the service it will render after it is built into the\nhome that is going to make your family so contented.\nThe largest yards south of the Ohio and the most partic\nular mill work are at your service the moment you say the\nword, and what\u2019s more, if you\u2019d like us to confer with\nyour builder, your architect or yourself, we\u2019re sure that\nwe will be able to offer many valuable home-making sug\ngestions that will mean greater economy and comfort\nfor you.\nVDLAWN\n188\nLUMBER CO.\nwsumi \"JUST CALL-! main\nyards THAT\u2019S. ALL**\nMi\nBIRMINGHAM QUICK CHANGE RIM CO\nI such a repeal. His.attitude seems en\ntirely unsatisfactory.\"\nSUFF8 DISPLEASED\nMarlon, O., July 22.\u2014Representatives\nof the national woman s party, who\ncalled on Senator Harding- today for\naid in completing: ratification of the\nsuffrage amendment, anounced tonight\nthat they were not satisfied with his\nreply, and would continue their de\nmand that he take more direct action.\n\"Suffragists can feel only dissatis\nfaction,\" said Alice Paul, head of the\nparty, \"with Senator Harding\u2019s refusal\ntoday, in his reply to the woman's\nparty delegation, and in his acceptance\nspeech to take a positive stand for the\ncarrying out of the suffrage plank in 1\nI the republican platform.\n\"If Senator Harding refuses to live\nI up to the suffrage plank and contents\nhimself with \u2018earnestly hoping\u2019 and\n\u2018sincerely 'desiring\u2019 how can he expect\nthe country to take seriously the other\nI planks in his platform?\n\"The national woman\u2019s party will\ncontinue to demand that Senator Hard\ning carry out his platform by securing\na vote in support of ratification from\nthe delegation in the Tennessee legis\nlature when it meecs next month.\u201d\nrailroads\u2019 propose\n20 PER CENT RAISE\nIN PASSENGER RATE\n(Continued from Page One)\n\u201c2. All excess baggage rates to be\nIncreased 20 per cent\n\"3. Surcharge on sleeping and parlor\ncars to be made 50 per cent of the\ncharge for space occupied either in par\nlor or sleeping cars.\n\u201d4. Milk, increase all rates, both pas\nsenger and freight, same total percen\ntage applied to freight revenue.\n\"5. Freight and switching revenues\nto be increased sufficiently to yield the\nbglsfice of the revenue required to meet\nthe increased operating expenses due to\nthe labor board award, in addition to\nthe percentage increase already pro\nposed'.\"\nThe total increases from all sources\nof revenue In each of the three railroad\nclassification territories w*uld corre\nspond to the estimated increase of\nwages in those territories and would\nbe as follows:\nEastern, $318,729,925; southern, $69,\n909.495, and western, *237,281,655.\nUnder the executives' estimates the\nproposed increase in passenger rates\nwould yield an annual return of *111,\n668,982 In eastern territory, *29,826,400\nin southern, and *92,332.599 in western.\n\u00aehe additional increase in freight\nrates would be 10 per cent in eastern\nterritory, yielding *182.020.541: 8.5 per\ncent in southern territory, yielding *33..\n798,926, and 8.23 per cent in western\nterritory, yielding *122,551,208.\nThe total incrAse in freight ratfs re\nsulting from the two proposals of the\nrailroads would be 39.75 per cent in\neastern territory: 38.91 in sbuthern ter\nritory, and 32.03 in western territory.\nThe surcharge on Pullman ffres in\nthe east would be *17,556,108; In the\nsouth *\"5.852.036, and in the west *20.\n231.200. The increased charge on haul\ning milk would be *6,956,416 in the\neast: *252.115 in the south, and *1.453.\n558 in the west. The increase in excess\nbaggage charges were estimated at\n*527.888 in the east, *180.017 In the\nsouth, and *703,030 in the west.\nConvoy Stuck in Mod\nBy Associated Press\nMemphis, July 22,-The army trucR con\ncoy which left this city early today on\nts transcontinental tour to 1-os Angeles,\n:onight was reported deep in the mud be\ntween Robinsville. Miss., and Banks\\\nMiss., about fifteen miles north of Tunica,\nrunica was the scheduled night camp\nng place. It was not known how long\nhe convoy would be delayed, but mes\nsages Indicated some time would be re\nquired before the trip could-be resumed.\nJob\u2019s Grouch\nwould be unknown to history if he\nhad been' able to cure those famous\nboils with\nOintment\nFortunately for you It is a very mod\nern remedy. At your druggist, 50c\nmd $1. Medicated Soap 2oc.\nil","height":"27800","width":"19756"}}
